snippet.textDisplay:
I have to be a bit of a party pooper here: Quite a bit of that story is suspected to be apocryphal, exaggerated or just flat out BS. To my knowledge, nobody's ever managed to produce an incident report, damage report or repair paperwork for the other destroyer that was allegedly damaged during the anchor incident and the war diaries of the USS Cogswell and the USS Young (the ships Willy D was moored next to when she left to rendezvous with the USS Iowa) make no mention of such damage either. The depth charge incident is not mentioned in the logs of either Willy D or Iowa. The torpedo incident did happen (as did the court martial and clemency regarding Lawton Dawson) but there is no mention of the entire ship's company being arrested on their return to Bermuda in the base's records.

Carrying on there is, again, no mention in official records of the detonation of an Alaskan base commander's back garden (this is the kind of thing that generates paperwork) and nobody has ever adequately explained how a single drunken crewman managed to load and fire a 127mm gun that normally has a crew of at least 15 spread across several decks.

That said, if you want a replacement candidate, I'd like to point you to the Japanese cruiser Mogami.

The depth charge incident is not mentioned in the logs of either Willy D or Iowa.
